komotiv Mezdra players]]\n[[Category:FC Vihren Sandanski players]]\n[[Category:PFC Minyor Pernik players]]\n[[Category:FC Sportist Svoge players]]\n[[Category:PFC Dobrudzha Dobrich players]]\n[[Category:Lyubimetz 2007 players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Bulgaria-footy-midfielder-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mladen_Stoev"}
{"title_page": "Cha Seung-won", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|South Korean actor}}\n{{Korean name|Cha}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Cha Seung-won\n|image       = Cha Seung-won on September 24, 2012.jpg\n|caption     = Cha in September 2012\n|height      = {{height|m=1.88}}\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|6|7}}\n|birth_place = [[Seoul]], South Korea\n|occupation  = {{hlist|Actor|model}}\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|agent       = [[YG Entertainment]]\n|website     =\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Lee Soo-jin|1992}}\n|module      = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes|color=transparent\n|hangul      = {{linktext|\ucc28|\uc2b9|\uc6d0}}\n|hanja       = {{linktext|\u8eca|\u52dd|\u5143}}\n|rr          = Cha Seung-won\n|mr          = Ch'a S\u016dngw\u014fn}}\n}}\n'''Cha Seung-won''' (born June 7, 1970) is a South Korean actor, who began his career as an in-demand [[model (person)|fashion model]] in the 1990s. Cha achieved stardom through the hit comedy films ''[[Kick the Moon]]'' (2001), ''[[Jail Breakers]]'' (2002), ''[[My Teacher, Mr. Kim]]'' (2003), and ''[[Ghost House (2004 film)|Ghost House]]'' (2004). After proving his versatility in other genres, notably in the [[period drama|period]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] ''[[Blood Rain (film)|Blood Rain]]'' (2005) and the [[melodrama]] ''[[My Son (2007 film)|My Son]]'' (2007), Cha's popularity continued with the [[Korean drama|television series]] ''[[Bodyguard (2003 TV series)|Bodyguard]]'' (2003), ''[[The City Hall (TV series)|City Hall]]'' (2009), ''[[The Greatest Love]]'' (2011), and ''[[Hwayugi]]'' (2017).\n\n== Career ==\nCha dropped out of [[Sungkyunkwan University]],<ref name=\"naver\"/> and began a successful career as a fashion [[model (profession)|model]] in 1988.<ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010011818110515228 \"Cha Seung-won's Movie Picks\"]. 10Asia. January 18, 2010.</ref> He was cast in the TV [[sitcom]] ''New York Story'', which would eventually pave the way for his debut in film.<ref name=Paquet>[http://www.koreanfilm.org/actors2.html#chasw \"Actors and Actresses of Korean Cinema: Cha Seung-won\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224024525/http://www.koreanfilm.org/actors2.html#chasw |date=February 24, 2018 }}. Koreanfilm.org. Retrieved November 4, 2012.</ref>\n[[File:Cha Seung-Won.jpg|thumb|left|upright|In June 2010]]\nAlthough his debut film ''[[Holiday In Seoul]]'' (1997) and many of his subsequent roles did not establish him as a major star, he attracted attention in 2000 for his performance as an [[arson]]ist in the firefighting film ''[[Libera Me (2000 film)|Libera Me]]''. The following summer, the runaway success of [[Kim Sang-jin (film director)|Kim Sang-jin]]'s comedy ''[[Kick the Moon]]'' (over 4.3 million tickets sold) secured his place in the industry as a leading actor with strong star appeal.<ref name=Paquet /> Since then, Cha has become one of the few surefire box office draws in the country. In a 2005 survey of influential movie producers, he was ranked among the top ten most bankable stars.<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2005/10/20/2005102061017.html \"Jang Dong-gun Voted Korea's Most Bankable Star\"]. [[The Chosun Ilbo]]. October 20, 2005.</ref>\n\nIn early 2003, Cha took on a slightly more serious role as a corrupt schoolteacher who is transferred to a country school in the film ''[[My Teacher, Mr. Kim]]''. The film grossed over 2.4 million admissions and drew Cha additional praise for his acting abilities (he would later team up again with director Jang Gyu-seong for 2007 comedy ''[[Small Town Rivals]]''<ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20070323000011 \"''Small Town Rivals'' puts comic twist on friendship\"]. [[The Korea Herald]]. March 22, 2007.</ref>). His next role, in ''[[Ghost House (2004 film)|Ghost House]]'', reunited him with director Kim Sang-jin in a successful comedy about a man who buys a dream home, only to discover it is haunted by a young female ghost.<ref name=Paquet />\n\nIn 2005 Cha put aside the comic roles he had become known for and appeared in the grisly [[period drama|period]] [[thriller (genre)|thriller]] ''[[Blood Rain (film)|Blood Rain]]''.<ref>[http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?biid=2005041414318 \"Dogged Cha Seung-won: Movie ''Tears of Blood''\"]. [[The Dong-a Ilbo]]. April 13, 2005.</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20130205032554/http://twitchfilm.com/reviews/2005/09/blood-rain-dvd-review.php \"K-FILM REVIEWS: \ud608\uc758 \ub204 (Blood Rain)\"]. [[Twitch Film]]. September 12, 2005.</ref> The film's unexpectedly robust commercial success confirmed Cha's popularity among Korean audiences.<ref name=Paquet /> He further proved his versatility in [[Jang Jin]]'s ''Murder, Take One'' (also known as ''The Big Scene'').<ref>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2005/08/02/2005080261023.html \"Cha Seung-won: Not Groomed for Stardom\"]. [[The Chosun Ilbo]]. August 2, 2005.</ref><ref>[http://www.koreaherald.com/national/Detail.jsp?newsMLId=20050811000024 \"''The Big Scene'' showcases a clever detective thriller\"]. [[The Korea Herald]]. August 11, 2005.</ref><ref>[http://twitchfilm.com/reviews/2006/01/korean-dvd-reviews-murder-take-one.php \"K-FILM REVIEWS: \ubc15\uc218\uce60 \ub54c \ub5a0\ub098\ub77c (Murder, Take One)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120720201206/http://twitchfilm.com/reviews/2006/01/korean-dvd-reviews-murder-take-one.php# |date=July 20, 2012 }}. [[Twitch Film]]. January 2, 2006.</ref>\n\nCha starred in his first [[melodrama]] ''[[Over the Border (2006 film)|Over the Border]]'' (2006), about a [[North Korean defector]].<ref>[http://www.hancinema.net/movie-reviewcomic-star-s-melodramatic-acting-in-south-of-the-border--5894.html \"Comic star's melodramatic acting in ''South of the Border''\"]. [[The Korea Herald]] via [[Hancinema]]. April 27, 2006.</ref><ref>[http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?biid=2006042785628 \"Go South\"]. [[The Dong-a Ilbo]]. April 27, 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.hancinema.net/-border--personal-stories-of-nk-defectors-5945.html \"''Border'', Personal Stories of NK Defectors\"]. [[The Korea Times]] via [[Hancinema]]. May 4, 2006.</ref> He then reunited with Jang Jin in ''[[My Son (2007 film)|My Son]]'' (2007), and he said his experience as a father helped a lot in learning the character.<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2014/01/135_1703.html \"Movies Reflect on Contemporary Fathers\"]. [[The Korea Times]]. April 24, 2007.</ref> Stylish crime thrillers ''[[Eye for an Eye]]'' (2008),<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/11/141_28136.html \"''Eye'' Spies Perfect Crime\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120813183822/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/11/141_28136.html |date=August 13, 2012 }}. [[The Korea Times]]. July 24, 2008.</ref> and ''[[Secret (2009 film)|Secret]]'' (2009) followed.<ref>[http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2913112 \"Thriller lays bare the secrets that we keep\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120710021421/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2913112# |date=July 10, 2012 }}. [[Korea JoongAng Daily]]. November 27, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=INTERVIEW: Cha Seung-won - Part 1|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009120217313516643|publisher=10Asia|date=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=INTERVIEW: Cha Seung-won - Part 2|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009120217321018754|publisher=10Asia|date=December 2, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=INTERVIEW: Cha Seung-won - Part 3|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2009120218163818715|publisher=10Asia|date=December 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCha returned to television in 2009, in the political fairytale ''[[The City Hall (TV series)|City Hall]]'' penned by writer [[Kim Eun-sook]].<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2009/04/135_43548.html \"''City Hall'' to Bring Public Officials to TV\"]. [[The Korea Times]]. April 21, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=More romantic comedy for prime time|url=http://view.koreaherald.com/kh/view.php?ud=20090429000088|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=April 29, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Male Actors Try New Roles in TV Dramas|url=http://english.kbs.co.kr/hallyu/entertainment_news_view.html?No=7059|publisher=KBS Global|date=July 2, 2009}}</ref> 2010 was a busy year for him,<ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010042714301098267 \"Interview: Actor Cha Seung-won - Part 1\"]. 10Asia. April 27, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010042720410246212 \"Interview: Actor Cha Seung-won - Part 2\"]. 10Asia. April 27, 2010.</ref> with Cha appearing in two films, the [[Lee Joon-ik]]-helmed period actioner ''[[Blades of Blood]]'',<ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010042014274359239 \"Traces of Lee Joon-ik's work in ''Blades of Blood''\"]. 10Asia. April 20, 2010.</ref> and [[Korean War]] film ''[[71: Into the Fire]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Korean War resurrected onscreen|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2012/10/201_65690.html|publisher=[[The Korea Times]]|date=May 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent5&idxno=2010051118200283206 \"TOP says lived as 17-year-old for 6 months for ''Fire'' (1)\"]. 10Asia. May 11, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?sec=ent5&idxno=2010051118195781049 \"TOP says lived as 17-year-old for 6 months for ''Fire'' (2)\"]. 10Asia. May 11, 2010.</ref> followed by spy series ''[[Athena: Goddess of War]]''.<ref>[http://english.kbs.co.kr/hallyu/entertainment_news_view.html?No=7496 \"Will ''Athena'' Exceeds Popularity of ''IRIS''?\"]. KBS Global. September 1, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2010/11/201_77213.html \"''Athena'' to sneak into homes this month\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003212418/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2010/11/201_77213.html |date=October 3, 2012 }}. [[The Korea Times]]. November 30, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010120310331441754 \"Preview: SBS TV series ''Athena''\"]. 10Asia. December 3, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2929090 \"'Iris' spinoff set for its small-screen debut\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120709171800/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2929090# |date=July 9, 2012 }}. [[Korea JoongAng Daily]]. December 7, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn 2011 his character in the hit romantic comedy series ''[[The Greatest Love]]'', arrogant top star \"Dokko Jin,\" became a mini pop culture phenomenon, giving rise to numerous commercial deals and parodies, as well as awards for Cha.<ref>[http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/05/201_86326.html \"TV soap to peek into celebrity life\"]. [[The Korea Times]]. May 3, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2011062317515477833 \"Preview: Cha Seung-won: I wanted to show the cute side to men\"]. 10Asia. June 23, 2011.</ref><ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2011062711172155537 \"Interview: Actor Cha Seung-won\"]. 10Asia. June 27, 2011.</ref>\n\nCha made his theater debut in 2012 in the stage play ''Bring Me My Chariot Fire'' alongside Japanese actors [[Tsuyoshi Kusanagi]], [[Ry\u014dko Hirosue]], [[Teruyuki Kagawa]], and Korean veteran actor [[Kim Eung-soo]]. Set in the historically turbulent early 1900s, the plot focuses on the friendship of artists from Korea and Japan who work together to preserve traditional Korean arts.<ref>[http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2012090715262751692 \"Cha Seung-won to expand career into play\"]. 10Asia. September 7, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cha Seung-won stars in Tokyo play|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2961829|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=November 6, 2012|access-date=November 6, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126203509/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2961829|archive-date=January 26, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Korean, Japanese actors come together in ''Chariot''|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2961970|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=November 8, 2012|access-date=November 8, 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127024439/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2961970|archive-date=January 27, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Cha signed with the talent agency [[YG Entertainment]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Veteran actor Cha works with YG|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2014/01/386_150108.html|publisher=[[The Korea Times]]|date=January 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=YG Entertainment signs more actors|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2983794|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=January 21, 2014}}</ref> then starred in the police series ''[[You're All Surrounded]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lee Seung-gi, Cha Seung-won, Go Ara Confirm New Drama|url=http://www.tenasia.com/lee-seung-gi-cha-seung-won-go-ara-confirm-new-drama/|publisher=10Asia|date=February 26, 2014|access-date=April 1, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329042727/http://www.tenasia.com/lee-seung-gi-cha-seung-won-go-ara-confirm-new-drama/|archive-date=March 29, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> This was followed by his third team-up with director Jang Jin in the comedy [[neo-noir|noir]] film ''[[Man on High Heels]]'', which subverted Cha's \"macho\" image by having him play a [[transgender]] homicide detective.<ref>{{cite web|title=Still cuts show Cha Seung-won garnered as woman in ''High Heel'' (2014)|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140529001648|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=May 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gender focus of noir film|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2989975|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=June 2, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Cha appeared in ''Three Meals a Day: Fishing Village'', a cable [[reality show]] set on the remote Manjae Island for which he earned the nickname \"Chajumma\" (from the word ''[[ajumma]]'') because of his versatile cooking skills despite the minimal amount of ingredients and implements.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Three Meals a Day'' spawns spinoff|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2999552|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=January 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=''Chajumma'' signs ad deals|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3002149|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=March 21, 2015}}</ref> He was then cast as [[Gwanghaegun of Joseon|Prince Gwanghae]] in the period drama ''[[Splendid Politics]]'', which focused on power struggles for the throne amid the backdrop of the [[Joseon Dynasty]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cha Seung-won has to act hungry for power|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3002331|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gwanghaegun returns in ''factional'' drama |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/04/201_176687.html |publisher=[[The Korea Times]] |date=April 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150410013652/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/04/201_176687.html |archivedate=April 10, 2015 }}</ref> Cha next plays cartographer and geologist [[Kim Jeong-ho]] in [[Kang Woo-suk]]'s period epic ''Gosanja, [[Daedongyeojido]]'', adapted from [[Park Bum-shin]]'s novel ''The Map Maker''.<ref>{{cite web|title=CHA Seung-won Boards Period Epic|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?mode=VIEW&seq=3426|publisher=Korean Film Biz Zone|date=May 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Cha was cast in tvN's fantasy romantic comedy drama ''[[A Korean Odyssey]]'' by the [[Hong sisters]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mengnews.joins.com/view.aspx?aId=3039508|title=Cha Seung-won will star in tvN\u2019s \u2018Hwayugi\u2019|date=October 17, 2017|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Cha starred in the family comedy-drama film ''[[Cheer Up, Mr. Lee]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=2&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4854&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=|title=PARK Hae-joon Joins CHA Seung-won for CHEER UP MYSTERY|date=June 19, 2018|website=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref> The same year, he was cast in the disaster film ''Sinkhole''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreanfilm.or.kr/eng/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=5215&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=|title=CHA Seung-won, KIM Sung-kyun and LEE Kwang-soo Fall into SINKHOLE|date=August 23, 2019|work=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCha and his wife Lee Soo-jin are biological parents to daughter Cha Ye-ni (born 2003, christened as Rachel). In July 2014, a man claiming to be the birth father of Cha and Lee's son Cha No-ah (born 1989, christened as Noah)<ref>[http://www.hancinema.net/cha-seung-won-reveals-his-son-noah-already-20-years-old-36113.html \"Cha Seung-won reveals his son Noah, already 20 years old\"]. Newsen via [[Hancinema]]. December 8, 2011.</ref> filed (and quickly dropped) a {{SK won|100 million}} [[defamation]] lawsuit against Cha, which led to the actor admitting that No-ah is Lee's son from her previous marriage, and that when he and Lee got married, Cha legally adopted No-ah, who was then three years old. Cha had previously falsified his marriage date as 1989 to match No-ah's age, apologizing for the [[white lie]] since their son did not know his paternity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cha Seung-won is sued by wife's ex|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=2995728|publisher=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cha Seung-won cleared of libel charges|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20141008001307|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|date=October 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Holiday In Seoul|Holiday in Seoul]]''\n| Leg model's boyfriend\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[If the Sun Rises in the West]]''\n| Ji-min\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3| 1999\n| ''[[Ghost in Love]]''\n| Na Han-su\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Attack the Gas Station]]''\n|\n| [[Bit part]]\n|-\n| ''Fin de Siecle''\n| Sang-woo\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2000\n| ''Black Honeymoon''\n| Kim Joon-ho\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Libera Me (2000 film)|Libera Me]]''\n| Yeo Hee-su\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Kick the Moon]]''\n| Choi Ki-woong\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2002\n| ''[[Break Out (film)|Break Out]]''\n| Yang Cheol-gon\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Jail Breakers]]''\n| Choi Mu-seok\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[My Teacher, Mr. Kim]]''\n| Kim Bong-doo\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2004\n| ''[[Ghost House (2004 film)|Ghost House]]''\n| Park Pil-gi\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Lovely Rivals]]''\n| Kim Bong-doo \n|[[cameo appearance|Cameo]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2005\n| ''[[Blood Rain (film)|Blood Rain]]''\n| Lee Won-gyoo\n|\n|-\n| ''Murder, Take One''\n| Choi Yeon-gi\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Over the Border (2006 film)|Over the Border]]''\n| Kim Sun-ho\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2007\n|''[[Small Town Rivals]]''\n| Jo Choon-sam\n|\n|-\n| ''[[My Son (2007 film)|My Son]]''\n| Lee Kang-shik\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Eye for an Eye (2008 film)|Eye for an Eye]]''\n| Ahn Hyun-min\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Secret (2009 film)|Secret]]''\n| Kim Seong-yeol\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2010\n| ''[[Blades of Blood]]''\n| Lee Mong-hak\n|\n|-\n| ''[[71: Into the Fire]]''\n| Park Moo-rang\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''The Suck Up Project: Mr. XXX-Kisser''\n| Cha Seung-won \n|[[cameo appearance|Cameo]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Man on High Heels]]'' \n| Yoon Ji-wook\n|\n|-\n| 2015 \n| ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]''\n| Narrator\n| [[voice acting|Voice]], [[Korean language|Korean]] [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201505181736489635124_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Cha Seung-won to star in \u2018Minions\u2019 as voice actor|date=May 18, 2015|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''The Map Against The World''\n| [[Kim Jeong-ho]]\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Believer (2018 Korean film)|Believer]]''\n| Brian \n| Special appearance<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreanfilm.or.kr/jsp/news/news.jsp?pageIndex=1&blbdComCd=601006&seq=4587&mode=VIEW&returnUrl=&searchKeyword=|title=LEE Hae-young\u2019s DOKJEON Wraps with CHO Jin-woong and RYU Jun-yeol|date=December 1, 2017|work=Korean Film Biz Zone}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[Cheer Up, Mr. Lee]]''\n| Chul-soo\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sinkhole''\n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''New York Story'' \n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| rowspan=5| 1998\n| ''Song of the Wind'' \n| \n|-\n| ''Woman vs. Woman'' \n|\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| ''Run Barefoot'' \n|\n|-\n| ''Shy Lovers'' \n| Im Sung-bom\n|-\n| ''Angel's Kiss'' \n| Jang Tae-ju\n| [[KBS2]]\n|-\n| rowspan=4| 1999\n| ''Roses and Bean Sprouts'' \n| Choi Gyu-dae\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| ''Sunday Best'' \"Someone Is Watching Me\"\n|\n| [[KBS2]]\n|-\n| ''Woman on Top'' <!--aka Have a Taste-->\n| Seung-il\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| ''Love Story'' \"Message\" \n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Bodyguard (2003 TV series)|Bodyguard]]'' \n| Hong Kyung-tak\n| [[KBS2]]\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[The City Hall (TV series)|City Hall]]'' \n| Jo Gook\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Athena: Goddess of War]]'' \n| Son Hyuk\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Greatest Love]]'' \n| Dokko Jin\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[You're All Surrounded]]'' \n| Seo Pan-seok\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Splendid Politics]]'' \n| [[Gwanghaegun of Joseon|Prince Gwanghae]]\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[A Korean Odyssey]]''\n| Woo Hwi-chul\n| [[tvN]] \n|}\n\n===Variety shows===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n|-\n| rowspan=4|1998\n| ''[[Lee Seung-yeon]]'s Say Say Say''\n| Co-host\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| ''GO! Our Heaven''\n| Host\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| ''[[Kim Hye-soo]] Plus You''\n| Co-host\n| [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]\n|-\n| ''Music Camp''\n| [[MC]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Cha Seung-won's Health Club'' ([[Sunday Night (South Korean TV series)|Sunday Sunday Night]])\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Cast member \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Three Meals a Day: Fishing Village''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]]\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Three Meals a Day: Gochang Village''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Korean Hostel in Spain]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/Article.aspx?aid=3060567|title=\u2018Korean Hostel in Spain\u2019 is open for business|date=March 15, 2019|website=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> \n|}\n\n===Music video appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! Year\n! Song title\n! Artist\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 1998\n| \"Even if the World Fools You\"\n| [[Kim Jang-hoon]]\n|-\n| \"Poison\"\n| [[Uhm Jung-hwa]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| \"I am a Man\"\n| [[Kim Jang-hoon]]\n|-\n| 2001\n| \"I Love You\"\n| Position\n|-\n| 2002\n| \"In My Heart\"\n| 4U \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Project X''\n| <ref>[http://www.yesasia.com/us/project-x-original-music-dvd-dvd-cd/1002522659-0-0-0-en/info.html \"Project X - Original Music DVD\"]. [[YesAsia]]. March 14, 2003.</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| \"Rain Shower\"\n| [[Kim Jang-hoon]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| \"Cry Cry\"\n|